    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-11-15T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-11-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="463"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d463">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/11–1548: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-15T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 15, 1948—1 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 15—2:07 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2406. Dr. Carsun Chang<note n="90" xml:id="d463fn90">Chairman of the Democratic
                        Socialist Party.</note> called and left with me message for General Marshall
                    forwarded in immediately succeeding telegram. He <pb facs="0578" n="568"
                        xml:id="pg_568"/> said that Chiang Kai-shek must go and that far from
                    weakening the anti-Communist front it would actually strengthen hands of such
                    leaders as Fu Tso-yi and Pai Chung-hsi if Generalissimo were eliminated from
                    picture. With his elimination anti-Communist generals could stabilize military
                    situation for some months provided American aid continued. This would enable
                    them to work out a peace. I pointed out that we could not intervene between
                    Chinese factions and asked whether Chinese pressure alone would be sufficient to
                    persuade Generalissimo to go. Dr. Chang said pressure from all quarters would in
                    his opinion be sufficient for this purpose. Dr. Chang said that Chinese were
                    sufficiently opposed to communism to continue civil war provided they did not
                    have fatal handicap of Generalissimo’s leadership.</p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated Nanking 1821.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
